nts":[{"name":"Cavin","meanings":["Scottish (Wigtownshire): variant of <b>Caveen</b>, a shortened form of Manx <i>Mac Dhaimhín</i>, son of <i>Daimhín</i>. The personal name is a diminutive of Gaelic <i>damh</i> ‘bard, poet’.","French: diminutive of   Cave  ."]},{"name":"Caves","meanings":["English: variant of   Cave  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Keeve","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Cave  . This surname is rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Chaffee","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): descriptive nickname from a derivative of Old French <i>chauf</i> ‘bald’ (from Latin <i>calvus</i>). Compare   Cave  ."]},{"name":"Cavett","meanings":["Scottish (of French origin): altered form of French <b>Cavet</b>, which is either a diminutive of   Cave   3 or a metonymic occupational name for a laborer, one who used a <i>cavet</i>, an Old Occitan word for a tool for clearing ground for cultivation."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":45,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud Cave was born in 1410, in Lincolnshire, England, her father, Alexander Cave, was 20 and her mother, Constantina Leeds, was 15. She had at least 1 daughter with Alexander Lound."},"et":{"1410–":"1410–Surnud","1396–Female":"1396–Surnud","1410–Female":"1410–Surnud","1410–1460":"1410–1460","1438–1474":"1438–1474","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1395–Female":"1395–Surnud","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1474":"1474","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","1460":"1460","Abt 1438":"umbes 1438","1390":"1390","1438":"1438","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"1410–":"1410–Kuollut","1396–Female":"1396–Kuollut","1410–Female":"1410–Kuollut","1410–1460":"1410–1460","1438–1474":"1438–1474","1390–Male":"1390–Kuollut","1395–Female":"1395–Kuollut","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1474":"1474","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","1460":"1460","Abt 1438":"noin 1438","1390":"1390","1438":"1438","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"fr":{"1410–":"1410–Décédée","1396–Female":"1396–Décédée","1410–Female":"1410–Décédée","1410–1460":"1410–1460","1438–1474":"1438–1474","1390–Male":"1390–Décédé","1395–Female":"1395–Décédée","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1474":"1474","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","1460":"1460","Abt 1438":"environ 1438","1390":"1390","1438":"1438","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Maud Cave est née en